{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564580"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:15:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:15:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16990"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16990"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.14,0.68,0.09,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68155"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9680"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16990"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53612"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3207"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35073"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68155"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent due to anxiety. She reports experiencing recurring thoughts about contamination and infection that cause her significant distress. She describes spending three hours each day washing her hands until they are raw and bleeding. She recognises these thoughts as excessive and irrational but feels unable to control them. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears anxious but otherwise well with vital signs within normal limits. Her hands show evidence of excessive washing with dry, cracked skin and some superficial bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best characterises these intrusive thoughts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thought broadcasting","Egosyntonic thoughts","Egodystonic thoughts","Delusional beliefs","Thought insertion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic example of obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) characterised by intrusive thoughts about contamination and compulsive hand washing. The key feature that helps identify these as \u003Cstrong\u003Eegodystonic thoughts\u003C/strong\u003E is that the patient recognises them as excessive and irrational, yet feels unable to control them. Egodystonic thoughts are experienced as intrusive, unwanted, and inconsistent with one\u0027s values and self-image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEgosyntonic thoughts\u003C/strong\u003E, in contrast, are consistent with one\u0027s values and self-image. For example, in anorexia nervosa, the thoughts about weight loss and body image are typically egosyntonic - the patient sees them as rational and aligned with their goals, even though they may be harmful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelusional beliefs\u003C/strong\u003E are fixed, false beliefs that are maintained despite evidence to the contrary. Unlike this patient\u0027s presentation, individuals with delusions typically lack insight into the irrationality of their beliefs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought broadcasting\u003C/strong\u003E is a psychotic symptom where an individual believes their thoughts are being transmitted to others. This is not present in this case, where the patient\u0027s distress comes from intrusive thoughts about contamination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThought insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is another psychotic symptom where an individual believes external thoughts are being placed into their mind. This differs from OCD where the thoughts are recognised as one\u0027s own, albeit unwanted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding whether thoughts are egodystonic or egosyntonic is crucial for treatment planning. Egodystonic thoughts in OCD typically respond well to a combination of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and cognitive behavioural therapy, particularly exposure and response prevention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Egodystonic thoughts are experienced as intrusive, distressing and inconsistent with one\u0027s values and self-image.","Obsessive-compulsive disorder typically features egodystonic thoughts, while anorexia nervosa typically features egosyntonic thoughts.","The distinction between egodystonic and egosyntonic thoughts helps guide therapeutic approach and risk assessment."],"references":["Sadock BJ, Sadock VA, Ruiz P. Kaplan and Sadock\u0027s comprehensive textbook of psychiatry. lippincott Williams \u0026 wilkins; 2017 May 11."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53612"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16990"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53612"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T10:30:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:31:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9680"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68155"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21